00:06:07,850 --> 00:06:16,055
which plays in any way we want. We can stack up whatever we want there and it just plays

58
00:06:16,055 --> 00:06:24,160
sound mass kind of thing with classical instruments. And in wormhole space it's similar, it's even

59
00:06:24,160 --> 00:06:34,106
more sinister. So it gets worse as it gets lower. So this is fine. I mean, this works

60
00:06:34,106 --> 00:06:34,726
up to a point.

61
00:06:36,368 --> 00:06:46,593
It sets the stage in most cases unless some players decide to change things because it's

62
00:06:46,593 --> 00:06:52,116
a sandbox. We don't know what's going to happen. We haven't set the story. So the players are

63
00:06:52,116 --> 00:06:54,597
really the ones that change the things there.

64
00:06:55,025 --> 00:06:59,587
So we don't know what they're going to do. We have no idea. So, for example, in empire

65
00:06:59,587 --> 00:07:07,392
space, you think it's safe. Sometimes we have kamikaze pilots fly into you and you're dead.

66
00:07:07,392 --> 00:07:15,857
Or some corporation declares war on you and you're just trying to mind and mind your own

67
00:07:15,857 --> 00:07:21,020
business. So that should change the music as well. But we still have the same kind of

68
00:07:21,020 --> 00:07:23,321
music there. It's easygoing and so on.

69
00:07:25,535 --> 00:07:34,002
And likewise in LOSAC or CERO, if there's a big corporation there that has a station

70
00:07:34,002 --> 00:07:39,908
there and a lot of players, it's not very difficult for them to stay there. So maybe

71
00:07:39,908 --> 00:07:44,532
the music is too much in that case for them to be like it is.

72
00:07:44,532 --> 00:07:50,357
So let's hear what these sound like just so you get an idea.

73
00:07:58,024 --> 00:08:04,930
This is Empire Space, where everything is fine and dandy.

74
00:08:04,930 --> 00:08:16,760
You can go around and mine, fly around, talk to your friends, have fun, and so on.

75
00:08:16,760 --> 00:08:21,624
All the music there is like easy going.

76
00:08:21,624 --> 00:08:23,346
And very nice.

77
00:08:23,346 --> 00:08:26,308
You can listen to it for hours.

78
00:08:27,288 --> 00:08:29,869
It's nice.

79
00:08:29,869 --> 00:08:33,452
Then Losec.

80
00:08:33,452 --> 00:08:35,973
Similar but a little more sinister, maybe.

81
00:08:35,973 --> 00:08:39,916
It gives an idea of, well, maybe I shouldn't be here.

82
00:08:39,916 --> 00:08:41,617
And it's...

83
00:08:41,617 --> 00:08:49,161
Yeah, it's not very frightening, but a little bit, at least.

84
00:08:49,161 --> 00:08:50,102
So it tells you something.

85
00:08:55,818 --> 00:09:01,019
Then if you go to zero, it's like this. It's like clusters of

86
00:09:01,019 --> 00:09:09,521
things that you hear that are stacked up randomly in wires.

87
00:09:09,521 --> 00:09:14,622
It's a very nice feature. You can do it any number of ways

88
00:09:14,622 --> 00:09:21,884
randomly. And you shouldn't hear much of repeated segments,

89
00:09:21,884 --> 00:09:22,184
but

90
00:09:22,940 --> 00:09:26,283
It still comes up, but it works really well.

91
00:09:26,283 --> 00:09:29,145
Up to a certain point, of course.

92
00:09:29,145 --> 00:09:41,615
And then we have wormhole space, which is, if you go there and you hear this,

93
00:09:41,615 --> 00:09:44,878
you probably are just frightened. You want to go back.

94
00:09:44,878 --> 00:09:48,000
So that's what it tells you.

95
00:09:49,925 --> 00:09:55,488
You're not flying around and having fun. It's like you shouldn't be alone there.

96
00:09:55,488 --> 00:10:11,477
So we basically want an intelligent music system.

97
00:10:11,477 --> 00:10:18,341
Because we can't, or maybe shouldn't.

98
00:10:19,120 --> 00:10:24,586
really precompose all of the elements in a game that ‑‑ or a story that hasn't

99
00:10:24,586 --> 00:10:32,313
taken place? Is it really fair to compose everything in a game that doesn't have a story

100
00:10:32,313 --> 00:10:38,299
that hasn't happened? I think we should find ways of making this better.

101
00:10:40,424 --> 00:10:46,108
Also hearing the same piece of music over and over again diminishes, causes diminishing

102
00:10:46,108 --> 00:10:51,111
aesthetic return and sometimes just makes us ignore it completely.

103
00:10:51,111 --> 00:10:59,958
So even if we had a budget of composing thousands of minutes of music, which is like a million

104
00:10:59,958 --> 00:11:01,699
dollars or something, or two million, I don't know.

105
00:11:02,828 --> 00:11:08,812
It will still happen. We will still hear the same thing over and over if we have a game

106
00:11:08,812 --> 00:11:13,915
that plays for more than ten years. That's just going to happen. We will end up with

107
00:11:13,915 --> 00:11:22,220
the repeated segments because of that. So that's why we want an intelligent music

108
00:11:22,220 --> 00:11:27,864
system. We want it to be able to create musical material by itself.

109
00:11:29,762 --> 00:11:39,664
So with some help from us, of course, as composers, but it should be able to create the material

110
00:11:39,664 --> 00:11:46,586
according to the atmosphere of the game, though. It should evolve according to the actual progression

111
00:11:46,586 --> 00:11:56,368
in the game in real time. It should be possible to control various musical parameters in music

112
00:11:56,368 --> 00:11:57,168
simultaneously.

113
00:11:58,113 --> 00:12:02,296
This is our wish list that we made. This is what we want.

114
00:12:02,296 --> 00:12:07,900
So the first steps in this direction we took in 2009. This wasn't like, ah, we have to

115
00:12:07,900 --> 00:12:15,366
have this tomorrow. We have to have this now. That's not going to happen. And we knew that

116
00:12:15,366 --> 00:12:21,250
it was not going to happen. So it was a side project. We started looking at what others

117
00:12:21,250 --> 00:12:26,653
had done, such as EA with Spore and some other nice projects.

118
00:12:27,550 --> 00:12:33,212
some really interesting things. We took a look at Max MSP and PT, if we could use that.

119
00:12:33,212 --> 00:12:44,676
But we want to have a system that can create real music, not just atmosphere. So it made

120
00:12:44,676 --> 00:12:52,579
it a little bit more complicated. We started researching with Dr. Kertan Olavsson

121
00:12:53,491 --> 00:12:58,136
He was a professor at the Atlantic academy of the arts at the time to find better ways

122
00:12:58,136 --> 00:13:00,619
of playing music in a sandbox game.

123
00:13:00,619 --> 00:13:07,546
We started at the beginnings of music with the basics of music.

124
00:13:07,546 --> 00:13:12,952
Intervals, tempo, rhythm, harmony, et cetera.

125
00:13:12,952 --> 00:13:14,494
And then on to methods.

126
00:13:15,160 --> 00:13:23,085
systems such as probability distributions and other methods in order to realize and

127
00:13:23,085 --> 00:13:29,289
identify what kind of a system could work. Then we took a look at Kertan's own system,

128
00:13:29,289 --> 00:13:36,873
which he called Kalmus, that system he had been working on for more than 20 years, which

129
00:13:36,873 --> 00:13:38,814
he wrote.

130
00:13:40,602 --> 00:13:48,464
to be able to make contemporary orchestral and instrumental music for himself, really.

131
00:13:48,464 --> 00:13:54,625
And now I'm going to hand the mic over to Kertan, and he's going to tell you a little

132
00:13:54,625 --> 00:13:59,806
bit about KalMes.

133
00:13:59,806 --> 00:14:01,647
Hello, everyone.

134
00:14:03,335 --> 00:14:11,582
I'm going to speak a little bit about this system and why this system became a composing system.

135
00:14:11,582 --> 00:14:17,528
When I was studying at the Sibelius Academy in Finland in the 80s,

136
00:14:17,528 --> 00:14:23,272
we got the opportunity to work with both professional composers and programmers.

137
00:14:24,614 --> 00:14:33,838
And at that time it was possible for normal people to learn how to program with personal computers.

138
00:14:33,838 --> 00:14:40,301
And since in music composition and mathematics has been used for at least a thousand years, as we know,

139
00:14:40,301 --> 00:14:43,983
but most of it was from the last century,

140
00:14:43,983 --> 00:14:50,026
we decided to construct a program as my thesis in my doctoral studies there.

141
00:14:51,648 --> 00:14:56,550
And first of all, the idea was to compose, to make a composing program

142
00:14:56,550 --> 00:15:04,232
that could use musical elements and materials, as we are doing with pens and papers.

143
00:15:04,232 --> 00:15:15,856
And use these new tools to make experiments with music, try to find new ways to compose music.

144
00:15:15,856 --> 00:15:17,116
And in the end...

145
00:15:20,242 --> 00:15:24,404
We had this program that could compose music for orchestra,

146
00:15:24,404 --> 00:15:27,465
for chamber music, electronic music.

147
00:15:27,465 --> 00:15:36,128
And now today, we are focusing on real time.

148
00:15:37,076 --> 00:15:40,619
composing, which is my interest, actually.

149
00:15:40,619 --> 00:15:46,363
But when the CCP people came to me and we started to talk about this, it was incredible

150
00:15:46,363 --> 00:15:50,666
that we were thinking about the same things.

151
00:15:50,666 --> 00:15:55,790
A composition for an orchestra is sometimes called three-level composition.

152
00:15:55,790 --> 00:16:00,593
In computer games, music, it's also three levels.

153
00:16:00,593 --> 00:16:06,318
Because this system is working with artificial intelligence.

154
00:16:08,634 --> 00:16:11,975
it was obvious that this could be used in a game,

155
00:16:11,975 --> 00:16:13,696
because artificial intelligence,

156
00:16:13,696 --> 00:16:17,397
which I will talk about a little later more,

157
00:16:17,397 --> 00:16:20,919
is something that can handle new situation

158
00:16:20,919 --> 00:16:22,899
with new preferences every time,

159
00:16:22,899 --> 00:16:23,540
every step in the process.

160
00:16:23,540 --> 00:16:25,720
So a composition with Kalmas is based on musical object,

161
00:16:25,720 --> 00:16:25,780
and

162
00:16:35,321 --> 00:16:40,264
We are talking about melodies, harmony, and development,

163
00:16:40,264 --> 00:16:43,446
polyphony, and so on, which is a common concept

164
00:16:43,446 --> 00:16:45,408
in composition without computers as well.

165
00:16:51,192 --> 00:16:55,814
The parameters we are working with are themes,

166
00:16:55,814 --> 00:16:57,995
which we create melodies from,

167
00:16:57,995 --> 00:17:01,377
harmony that will decide what kind of connections

168
00:17:01,377 --> 00:17:02,597
are between the melodies,

169
00:17:02,597 --> 00:17:06,639
scales, which we know mostly today

170
00:17:06,639 --> 00:17:08,620
we are using major and minor,

171
00:17:08,620 --> 00:17:11,702
texture, polyphony, et cetera.

172
00:17:11,702 --> 00:17:16,104
And the musical material is quite traditional,

173
00:17:16,104 --> 00:17:20,306
cells which creates the melody.

174
00:17:21,641 --> 00:17:23,982
and harmony that will connect them together.

175
00:17:23,982 --> 00:17:27,503
And polyphony structures, how they actually are talking

176
00:17:27,503 --> 00:17:28,683
to each other, the melodies.

177
00:17:28,683 --> 00:17:32,004
The algorithms we are using, they take care of putting

178
00:17:32,004 --> 00:17:33,965
together tones for harmony and for melodies.

179
00:17:45,694 --> 00:17:50,458
And we are using, in a very traditional way, different scales.

180
00:17:50,458 --> 00:17:55,843
And the scales in our time, they are reflecting a different geographical position, like we

181
00:17:55,843 --> 00:17:57,444
have Japanese scales, European scales, and so on.

182
00:17:57,444 --> 00:18:00,466
And the artificial intelligence system makes it possible for the system to go on, to compose

183
00:18:00,466 --> 00:18:00,747
music by itself.

184
00:18:14,378 --> 00:18:20,080
But as we are doing it, the composer using the system

185
00:18:20,080 --> 00:18:24,022
is defining the framework, creating the material,

186
00:18:24,022 --> 00:18:29,444
and deciding what kind of color or texture it will contain.

187
00:18:29,444 --> 00:18:36,806
So, one simple example about artificial intelligence,

188
00:18:36,806 --> 00:18:40,127
when creating a new pitch in melody construction,

189
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:44,382
And as you can see on this picture,

190
00:18:44,382 --> 00:18:46,824
there are graphic annotation,

191
00:18:46,824 --> 00:18:54,291
there are four notes that are called last pitches

192
00:18:54,291 --> 00:18:56,212
plus a test pitch.

193
00:18:57,413 --> 00:19:02,297
And these pitches, they are compared to the input cell from the composer.

194
00:19:02,297 --> 00:19:10,724
And the program is deciding what are the relations between this new pitch in this new melodic

195
00:19:10,724 --> 00:19:15,068
line according to the actual input cell from the composer.

196
00:19:16,613 --> 00:19:19,515
And what happens when it finally is accepted,

197
00:19:19,515 --> 00:19:23,617
after having been compared to what kind of scale,

198
00:19:23,617 --> 00:19:27,039
what kind of interval are preferred,

199
00:19:27,039 --> 00:19:30,441
then the new pitch is accepted,

200
00:19:30,441 --> 00:19:35,763
and there's a new situation in the middle construction.

201
00:19:35,763 --> 00:19:40,286
And that means that the program has to continue

202
00:19:40,286 --> 00:19:44,248
to make another selection according to this new situation.

203
00:19:45,740 --> 00:19:49,382
And this is called artificial intelligence in music creation.

204
00:19:49,382 --> 00:19:58,929
The same things or quite similar things are happening in the computer game, like sandbox

205
00:19:58,929 --> 00:20:02,691
as they are working with, working on.

206
00:20:02,691 --> 00:20:07,555
It is something happens in the game and a new situation have occurred.

207
00:20:11,002 --> 00:20:14,062
And then the program like this can actually decide,

208
00:20:14,062 --> 00:20:16,003
we have to change the musical texture

209
00:20:16,003 --> 00:20:18,943
and prepare for another development of the music.

210
00:20:18,943 --> 00:20:20,003
And to do this, we made several project

211
00:20:20,003 --> 00:20:21,164
just to connect this computer composing system

212
00:20:21,164 --> 00:20:21,464
to the actual game.

213
00:20:36,010 --> 00:20:38,071
And the first one is called Kalmas Waves,

214
00:20:38,071 --> 00:20:42,033
which is we are using dances to control the program.

215
00:20:42,033 --> 00:20:45,575
And this Kalmas program can be controlled.

216
00:20:45,575 --> 00:20:50,997
Each parameter can be changed in real time,

217
00:20:50,997 --> 00:20:54,058
which means that we can take music from the 20th century,

218
00:20:54,058 --> 00:20:58,980
change the harmony and the polyphonic structure,

219
00:20:58,980 --> 00:21:02,762
and we can go back in time to the 15th century

220
00:21:02,762 --> 00:21:05,763
by doing this without changing the material.

221
00:21:08,528 --> 00:21:12,972
And to do this we created, constructed a census connected to the dances and the dances are

222
00:21:12,972 --> 00:21:15,755
sending messages to the program that will compose according to their movements.

223
00:21:15,755 --> 00:21:18,617
This is what we can use in the computer games, taking messages from the games and use the

224
00:21:18,617 --> 00:21:20,980
message to compose music according to what is happening.

225
00:21:36,337 --> 00:21:44,080
The second thing we did is called Kalmus Play, which is kind of an app for fun to create

226
00:21:44,080 --> 00:21:51,103
very simple music. And what this is doing, it's this simple app is communicating with

227
00:21:51,103 --> 00:21:54,444
the program, a special version of the program, which is on the server in Europe, in Iceland,

228
00:22:00,388 --> 00:22:03,969
And this small app can compose music.

229
00:22:03,969 --> 00:22:12,912
So if I press this button, it will send a simple message to the server and compose the

230
00:22:12,912 --> 00:22:15,673
music and send it back.

231
00:22:15,673 --> 00:22:18,974
